quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to display the value of x to the screen three times.
[!raw!]
int x = 42;
int num = 0;
{0}(num < 3) {
  Console.WriteLine({1});
  num++;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]while[/h1]

A [b]while [/b]loop repeatedly executes a block of code as long as a given condition is [b]true[/b]. 
For example, the following code displays the numbers 1 through 5: [code format="cs" codeId="835"]int num = 1;
while(num < 6) 
{
   Console.WriteLine(num);
   num++;
}
/* Outputs
1
2
3
4
5
*/[/code]
The example above declares a variable equal to 1 (int num = 1).
The [b]while [/b]loop checks the condition (num < 6) and, if [b]true[/b], executes the statements in its body, which increment the value of [b]num [/b]by one, before checking the loop condition again. 
After the 5th iteration, [b]num [/b]equals 6, the condition evaluates to [b]false[/b], and the loop stops running.
[note]The [b]loop body [/b]is the block of statements within curly braces.[/note]

quizzes.question:
