int num = 0;
while ({0} < 100)
{
  Console.WriteLine(num);
  num{1}={2};
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The while Loop [/h1]

The compound arithmetic operators can be used to further control the number of times a loop runs. For example:[code format="cs" codeId="836"]int num = 1;
while(num < 6) 
{
   Console.WriteLine(num);
   num+=2;
}
/* Outputs
1
3
5
*/[/code] 
[note]Without a statement that eventually evaluates the loop condition to [b]false[/b], the loop will continue indefinitely.[/note]

quizzes.question:
How many times will the following loop execute?
int x = 1;
while (x++ < 5)
{
    if (x % 2 == 0)
        x += 2;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The while Loop[/h1]

We can shorten the previous example, by incrementing the value of [b]num [/b]right in the condition: [code format="cs" codeId="837"]int num = 0;
while(++num < 6) 
   Console.WriteLine(num);[/code]
[note]What do you think, is there a difference between [b]while(num++ < 6)[/b] and [b]while(++num < 6)[/b]?
Yes! The loop[b] while(++num < 6) [/b]will execute 5 times, because pre-increment increases the value of x before checking the num < 6 condition, while post-increment will check the condition before increasing the value of num, making [b]while(num++ < 6)[/b] execute 6 times.[/note]
